ding, and isotopic composition. [Data: Entities (211, 285, 746, 747, 748); Relationships (834, 835, 836, 2110)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Valence-shell and octet-rule concepts provide the explanatory framework tying most entities together.\",\"explanation\":\"The valence shell is explicitly defined as the outermost electron shell whose electrons are directly involved in chemical interactions, especially covalent bonding; it is directly linked to “electronic configuration” as a determinant of stability/reactivity. This framing underpins why chlorine (with seven valence electrons) tends to gain one electron (ionic) or share electrons (covalent) to achieve a complete octet. [Data: Entities (1405); Relationships (1997, 2169)]\\n\\nThe octet rule is operationalized in the relationships by repeatedly assessing whether bonding results in eight valence electrons (complete octet) or exceptions (incomplete/expanded). The community therefore clusters around teaching/interpretive constructs (valence shell, octet rule, exceptions) rather than around real-world compliance, legal, or reputational issues. [Data: Entities (1480, 1472, 1473); Relationships (2169, 2130, 2131)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Covalent bonding exemplars: HCl and Cl2 illustrate electron sharing to complete octets.\",\"explanation\":\"Hydrogen chloride (HCl) is explicitly described as forming when a chlorine atom shares a pair of electrons with hydrogen, producing a single covalent bond. This is used as a direct example of covalent bonding behavior involving chlorine to achieve a stable valence-shell arrangement. [Data: Entities (1440, 211, 1403); Relationships (2078, 2006)]\\n\\nChlorine (Cl2) is separately represented as a diatomic covalent molecule where two chlorine atoms share a bond pair and retain lone pairs that complete octets on each chlorine. This reinforces the chlorine-centered narrative: chlorine can meet octet stability either by bonding with another element (HCl) or with itself (Cl2). [Data: Entities (1463, 285